UNIT 1

1. Open Source Software (OSS)

  • Definition:
    • Software with publicly accessible source code.
    • Users can view, modify, and distribute the code.
  • Key Characteristics:
    • Access to Source Code: No secrecy; code is open for modification.
    • Collaboration: Global developer contributions.
    • Freedom to Use: No licensing fees; use for any purpose.
    • Community Support: Active user/developer communities.

2. Examples & Benefits of OSS

  • Examples:
    • Linux OS: Alternative to Windows/macOS.
    • Apache HTTP Server: Popular web server.
    • Mozilla Firefox: Web browser.
    • LibreOffice: Office suite.
  • Benefits:
    • Cost: Free to use.
    • Flexibility: Customizable code.
    • Security: Vulnerabilities fixed quickly (many contributors).
    • Transparency: Code visibility ensures trust.

3. Development Philosophy of OSS

  • Principles:
    • Collaboration: Global teamwork (like a “treehouse-building party”).
    • Transparency: No hidden code (“no secret recipes”).
    • Customization: Modify software freely (like LEGO blocks).
    • Inclusivity: All skill levels can contribute (“everyone’s a chef”).
    • Learning: Continuous improvement through trial and error (“Build, Break, Learn”).

4. Pros & Cons of OSS

Pros Cons
Cost-effective Lack of Support
Community Collaboration Less User-Friendly
Transparency Compatibility Issues
Customization Limited Features
Security Fragmentation
Freedom Poor Documentation

5. Open Source vs Closed Source Software

Aspect Open Source Closed Source
Access Source code publicly available Source code proprietary
Cost Free Paid licenses/subscriptions
Development Community-driven Company-controlled team
Examples Linux, Apache, Firefox Windows, Adobe Photoshop
Transparency High (code visible) Low (code hidden)

6. Community Support in OSS

  • Key Features:
    • Collaborative Problem-Solving: Fix bugs collectively (“solving puzzles as a team”).
    • Knowledge Sharing: Forums, documentation, and chat groups.
    • Continuous Improvement: Community-driven updates and features.
    • Support Network: No need to face issues alone (“group of friends”).

7. Websites & Webpages

  • Website: Collection of webpages under a domain (e.g., www.example.com).
  • Webpage: Single HTML document with text/images/videos.
    • Technologies: HTML (structure), CSS (styling), JavaScript (interactivity).

8. Static vs Dynamic Websites

Feature Static Dynamic
Content Fixed, manually updated HTML Generated on-the-fly (PHP, Python)
Loading Time Faster (pre-built) Slower (server processing)
Flexibility Low (requires coding for changes) High (CMS integration)
Example Small business site Social media (Facebook, Twitter)

9. Client-Side vs Server-Side Scripting

Aspect Client-Side Server-Side
Location Runs on user’s browser Runs on web server
Languages JavaScript, HTML, CSS PHP, Python, Ruby, Node.js
Function DOM manipulation, form validation Database operations, user auth
Example Button click animation User login authentication

10. Web Hosting Types

Type Description Pros Cons
Shared Multiple sites on one server Cost-effective Limited resources
Cloud Uses interconnected servers Scalable, reliable Variable costs
VPS Virtual private server More control, better performance Costlier than shared
Dedicated Entire server for one user Full control, high performance Expensive, needs expertise
